  abstract-en: (
    content: [
With the increasing integration of renewable energy sources, modern power systems exhibit strong nonlinearity, low inertia and the coexistence of multiple stochastic disturbances. Conventional methods based on deterministic models and local stability around equilibrium points are no longer adequate to fully assess the instability risk under large disturbances. This thesis takes the single-machine infinite-bus (SMIB) power system as the object, and combines nonlinear dynamics, stochastic dynamics and the composite cell coordinate system (CCCS) method to investigate the global stability of the system under the joint action of periodic load disturbances and Gaussian white noise.

A deterministic SMIB model with periodic load disturbance is first established, and bifurcation diagrams, the maximal Lyapunov exponent and steady-state amplitude sweep curves are employed to characterize the path from period-doubling to chaos and the final escape leading to instability. The CCCS method is then applied to depict the global safe basin, revealing that the safe basin undergoes fractal erosion as the disturbance amplitude increases. Gaussian white noise is further introduced to build a stochastic model, which shows that noise significantly smears the fine bifurcation structure, advances the critical threshold of instability, and intensifies the fractalization of the basin boundary together with the shrinkage of the effective safe area.

The results indicate that the combined action of deterministic disturbances and stochastic noise considerably weakens the global synchronization robustness of the power system. Safe basin erosion can therefore serve as an important precursor indicator of system instability, providing a new theoretical basis for stability margin assessment and risk warning of new-type power systems.
